</li><li id="tree_64247118" class="comment full contain"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64247118" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64247118" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64247118" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64247118" name="comment_link_64247118" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23229770&amp;cid=64247118" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64247118)" >They skipped algebra?</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64247118" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64247118); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Informative)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Fons_de_spons">Fons_de_spons</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Fons_de_spons">( 1311177 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64247118">		
		on Saturday February 17, 2024 @05:15AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23229770&amp;cid=64247118">#64247118</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64247118">So I am a math teacher. I teach 14 to 15 year Olds. Algebra is still on the menu here, but it is soften down over the years. Which is a disaster. Their math foundation is too weak to build on. We (colleagues, principal, school board) decided to keep our exams the same. Students are shocked when they start in September. They get angry. The verbally strong ones challenge me. It is your fault that our grades are so low. Sometimes they revolt. Then exams in December start. A quarter to half of them fail hard. Tears flow. It is februari now. Class is silent. They are starting to study in advance. Ask questions. Kids voluntary ask for extra exercises. Fractions are getting better. But we still have a long road ahead of us. The ones that really struggle get the message that they
may have to find a different school in the long run. We support them, and they keep trying, to my own surprise. <br>
I am a softy. I had lot of trouble with this approach when I started teaching. Colleagues encouraged me. Kids need this. They need to know it is complicated out there. But luckily not all of the courses are this hard for them.</div>
	</div>

